@foodmyfavorite The best choice is to turn off your tv. Get your news from real news outlets.

I have a lot of people emailing and messaging me right now who think the sky has fallen, it's all over, and Trump has magically gotten away with everything. My advice to them all has been the same: just turn off your television and everything will be fine...

Cable news has its place. Some of the hosts are actually quite insightful. But it's television, so you have to view it all through the filter television's own inherent need to keep you tuned in at all cost. On days like this, cable news is about as "real" as the Apprentice...

Remember when MSNBC & CNN spent a year saying Mueller was about to get fired? Remember when they spent six months saying everyone was about to get pardoned? Remember when Hillary was going to be indicted over her emails? Nonsense like that is why Palmer Report has to exist...

It's not that MSNBC and CNN are reporting fake stories, like Fox News. They're not. They just take real stories and spin them in whatever direction will keep you tuned in 24/7. Sometimes that means spinning in misleading directions....

I can admit to you that we won't know anything for a couple days, and if you don't read my articles between now and then, I don't mind. But cable news has huge operating budgets. They can't afford to acknowledge anything that might prompt you to go watch basketball instead...

MSNBC and CNN know that if they tell you SDNY indictments are likely once Mueller's report is public, you'll turn off the tv until after the report is public. You'll go to the beach instead. They have to find a way to keep you glued to the tv, so they're scaring you into it...

Adam Schiff & Richard Blumenthal, who know a lot more about this probe than anyone on TV, both called in to MSNBC and tried to set the record straight about indictments. MSNBC cut Blumenthal off mid sentence so it could keep pushing the "no one else will be indicted" narrative...

What we're seeing on MSNBC and CNN tonight is some of the most intentionally and grotesquely misleading coverage ever. They're falsely equating "no more Mueller indictments" with "no more indictments" to scare/outrage you into staying tuned in, when they know better...

Some of you get upset whenever I point out that MSNBC and CNN are misleading you, because you enjoy watching them. But I originally went into political journalism because of how inaccurately MSNBC and CNN were covering the 2016 election. Someone had to push back with the facts...

And yes, Warren, Booker, Klobuchar, Gillibrand etc have a chance. But the playing field would need to change to where they're getting more positive momentum than Kamala is currently getting. And yes, it's still very early.

So who's realistically the frontrunner? Biden and Kamala both. His poll numbers are already pretty good, and she has positive momentum that should result in her poll numbers climbing a lot over the next year. If I were Bernie I'd be worried; his support is fierce but narrow.

In summary, the polls tell us nothing about Kamala/Warren/etc yet. It's literally "are you familiar with this person yet?" But the Biden and Bernie numbers are revealing about how they're likely to fare, as the other candidates gave more name recognition...

The very bad news for Bernie is that, even with his huge name recognition from 2016, and even in a perceived two person 2020 primary race, he's losing to Biden pretty badly. There's no reason to expect Bernie to finish higher than second, and every reason to expect worse...

The mediocre news for Biden is that even with his huge name recognition, and even in a perceived two person race, he's "winning" but he's not dominating. 35% want Biden. But at least as many voters say they're waiting for someone else to emerge...

It's a very story for Kamala, Warren, Klobuchar, etc. As they spend more time in Iowa, and as they get more airtime in debates, etc, their name recognition will grow. Unless they bomb, their numbers will go up. They'll pull people away from "not sure" and from Biden and Bernie...

That means Biden and Bernie's numbers aren't likely to go any higher than they are right now, at least not any time soon.. Biden might get little bump when he actually enters the race. But they're both maxed out for now...

The average voter looks at the list of ten democratic candidates, and only really knows Biden and Bernie, and therefore sees it as a two person primary race. If they don't like either guy, they're picking "no one" or "not sure" for now, until they understand who the other are...

You're politically active, so you're highly familiar with all of the 2020 candidates, or at least the top six or seven. But to the average voter, only Biden and Bernie are fully fleshed out from past exposure. The other names are mere curiosities, blanks to be filled in later...

Let's talk about what the 2020 democratic primary polls really tell us this early on. It's a completely asymmetric playing field right now, where two candidates have huge name recognition, and the others don't yet. It's about whose numbers can move and whose can't...
